:"about 1400","1396":"1396","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1392":"1392","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1398":"about 1398","1339":"1339","Chorley, Lancashire, England":"Chorley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Duxbury, Lancs., Eng.":"Duxbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Duxbury, Lancashire, England":"Duxbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Standish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Standish (Lancashire, now part of Greater Manchester), from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure, enclosed park’. Standish (Gloucestershire) does not appear to have contributed towards the surname.","History: Myles Standish (<i>c.</i> 1584–1656) was a soldier of fortune, from 1620 captain of the <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony. Little is known of his origins and early life, but in his will he claimed to be descended from a leading Catholic family, the Standishes of Standish, Lancashire, England. He also claimed to have been deprived of his inheritance, a claim not confirmed."],"variants":[{"name":"Standage","meanings":["English:","probably a variant of   Standish  .","in Leicestershire and Buckinghamshire, the name may alternatively be from Stanedge Grange in Hartington Nether Quarter or Stanage End in Outseats (both Derbyshire); but evidence is needed for this. The placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, escarpment’."]}]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Christopher de Standish was born in 1375, in Duxbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Hugh de Standish. He married Margaret Le Fleming in 1396, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1437, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1375–1437":"1375–1437","1376–1442":"1376–1442","–1437":"–1437","1376–1440":"1376–1440","1392–1435":"1392–1435","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1400–1462":"1400–1462","1339–1421":"1339–1421","abt. 1400":"umbes 1400","1396":"1396","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1392":"1392","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1398":"umbes 1398","1339":"1339","Chorley, Lancashire, England":"Chorley, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa","Duxbury, Lancs., Eng.":"Duxbury, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Duxbury, Lancashire, England":"Duxbury, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1375–1437":"1375–1437","1376–1442":"1376–1442","–1437":"–1437","1376–1440":"1376–1440","1392–1435":"1392–1435","1398–Male":"1398–Kuollut","1400–1435":"1400–1435","1400–1462":"1400–1462","1339–1421":"1339–1421","abt. 1400":"noin 1400","1396":"1396","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1392":"1392